<article>
    <h1>At a glance</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201109/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-09"><time>2020-11-09</time></a>
        - <span>SINGAPORE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Malavika Menon</span>
    </section>

    <p>Es­tab­lished by the will of Cape Colony prime min­is­ter and di­a­mond mag­nate Ce­cil John Rhodes in 1902, the pres­ti­gious Rhodes Schol­ar­ship is deemed the old­est in­ter­na­tional schol­ar­ship pro­gramme in the world.</p>
    <p>It en­ables stu­dents to un­der­take full-time post­grad­u­ate stud­ies at the University of Ox­ford. Rhodes Schol­ars have gone on to be­come prom­i­nent po­lit­i­cal fig­ures, aca­demics, sci­en­tists and civil so­ci­ety lead­ers. Cel­e­brated as­tronomer Ed­win Hub­ble (1910) and for­mer US pres­i­dent Bill Clin­ton (1968) are among them.</p>
    <p>The award of the Rhodes Schol­ar­ship re­sumed in Sin­ga­pore in 2018, after it was sus­pended here and in sev­eral other coun­tries in 2006 due to fund­ing is­sues. Sin­ga­pore firm APS As­set Man­age­ment gifted an en­dow­ment of £4 mil­lion (S$7.1 mil­lion) to re­in­state the schol­ar­ship.</p>
    <p>No­table Sin­ga­pore­ans who were Rhode Schol­ars in­clude for­mer MP and Cab­i­net min­is­ter Raymond Lim and com­pet­i­tive swim­mer Des­mond Koh.</p>
    <p>Mr Lim was awarded the schol­ar­ship in 1984. He en­tered pol­i­tics in 2001 and was made a min­is­ter of state after be­ing elected. He served as trans­port min­is­ter be­fore leav­ing pol­i­tics in 2015.</p>
    <p>Mr Koh rep­re­sented Sin­ga­pore in 14 events at the 1988, 1992 and 1996 Olympics. He re­ceived the schol­ar­ship for his PhD de­gree in 1995.</p>


